INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd2da583a-6377-4cc7-af14-1e2f8302faad',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$JAX GPU Acceleration — Devices, jit, and Mixed Precision$escape$,
  $escape$JAX abstracts hardware through its device model — by default, arrays live on the default backend (CPU or GPU). Use `jax.devices()` to inspect available devices and `jax.device_put(x, device)` to explicitly place arrays on a specific GPU. Unlike PyTorch, JAX doesn't have a `.to(device)` method; placement is functional.

For mixed precision, JAX uses `jax.numpy` dtypes directly. Cast inputs to `jnp.bfloat16` (preferred on TPUs/modern GPUs over float16 due to better range) before feeding into your model, and keep optimizer state in float32 manually — JAX has no automatic loss scaling built in. Use `jax.lax.Precision` to control BLAS precision per-op.

`jax.jit` compiles and dispatches to whichever device holds the inputs — no explicit device annotation needed on the function itself. Mixing devices in a single jitted call will trigger a transfer, so keep data co-located. Profile with `jax.profiler` or `jax.block_until_ready()` to get accurate GPU timings rather than measuring lazy dispatch.$escape$,
  $escape$import jax
import jax.numpy as jnp

gpu = jax.devices('gpu')[0]

x = jnp.ones((1024, 1024))
x_gpu = jax.device_put(x, gpu)

# Mixed precision: cast to bfloat16 for compute
x_bf16 = x_gpu.astype(jnp.bfloat16)

@jax.jit
def matmul(a, b):
    return jnp.dot(a, b)

result = matmul(x_bf16, x_bf16)  # compiles & runs on GPU
jax.block_until_ready(result)    # force sync for accurate timing
print(result.dtype, result.device())  # bfloat16, CudaDevice(id=0)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
